<h2>Security: _blank and noopener</h2>
<p>Historically, <code>target="_blank"</code> gave the opened page access to <code>window.opener</code>, allowing it to redirect your original tab to a phishing page. This required adding <code>rel="noopener"</code> as a countermeasure.</p>
<p><strong>Modern browsers now imply <code>rel="noopener"</code> for all <code>target="_blank"</code> links by default.</strong> However, adding <code>rel="noopener noreferrer"</code> explicitly is still recommended for clarity and to support older browsers.</p>

<h2>Named Targets</h2>
<p>Any string that is not one of the underscore-prefixed keywords becomes a named browsing context. If a window or tab with that name already exists, the browser navigates it instead of opening a new one. This is useful for "preview" workflows.</p>

